Here's a C++ program that reads a text file line by line and counts the number of occurrences of a specific word in the file. In this example, we'll use the word "algorithm" as the specific word to count:
```cpp
#include <iostream>
#include <fstream>
#include <string>

int main() {
    std::string wordToCount("algorithm"); // Change this to the word you want to count
    std::ifstream inputFile("input.txt"); // Change this to the path of your input file

    if (!inputFile.is_open()) {
        std::cerr << "Failed to open the input file." << std::endl;
        return 1;
    }

    int wordCount = 0;

    std::string line;
    while (std::getline(inputFile, line)) {
        size_t position = line.find(wordToCount);
        if (position != std::string::npos) {
            wordCount++;
        }
    }

    inputFile.close();

    if (wordCount > 0) {
        std::cout << "The word '" << wordToCount << "' appears " << wordCount << " times in the file." << std::endl;
    } else {
        std::cout << "The word '" << wordToCount << "' was not found in the file." << std::endl;
    }

    return 0;
}
```

Make sure to replace `"input.txt"` with the actual path to your input text file and update the `wordToCount` variable to the word you want to count. This program reads the file line by line, checks each line for the presence of the specified word, and counts the occurrences.

Remember to compile the code with a C++ compiler (e.g., `g++`) and run the resulting executable. The program will read the file, count the occurrences of the specified word, and provide the result.

Please note that this program assumes that the input file contains only plain text and does not handle potential errors related to file permissions or non-existent files. You may want to add additional error handling and input validation based on your specific use case.
